sect1.para:
Given that SSRD had not been introduced before 2013 with the publication of the DSM-5 (American Psychiatric Association,
         2013
      ), high-quality epidemiological studies based on the DSM-5 (and DSM-5-TR) criteria are still scarce and the following summary will refer to older studies based on criteria of the predecessor of SSRD, the so-called Somatoform Disorders.

sect2.para:
Women tend
            tend
          to report somatic symptoms more commonly than men, an outcome that has been demonstrated across numerous studies of samples with less severe symptoms (Hiller et al., 
            2006
         ) as well as clinically relevant syndromes of SSD (Jacobi et al., 
            2004
         ). It seems however that gender-related distribution of symptom report is also influenced by cultural factors. A study by Piccinelli and Simon (
            1997
         ) showed that the higher prevalence in women is especially common in Western societies. Women also present more frequently with FNSD compared to men (60–75%) (Espay et al., 
            2018
         ). Regarding FD, the prevalence is as twice as high for women compared to men, and regarding FD by Proxy, most of the abusers are female and the victim’s mother (Yates & Bass, 
            2017
         ). IAD on the contrary seems to be relatively evenly distributed between men and women (Scarella et al., 
            2019
         ).

Individuals
   Individuals
 of higher age seem to report persistent somatic symptoms more frequently (Hiller et al., 
   2006
); however, it is unclear how much these symptoms are explained by nonspecific age-related degeneration. Interestingly, syndromes of multiple persistent somatic symptoms seem to be more common in younger age groups, between 18 and 34 years (Leiknes et al., 
   2007
). There have not been differences between IAD patients and the general population in terms of age (Scarella et al., 
   2019
). FNSD
   FNSD
 can occur across the lifespan (Feinstein, 
   2018
). The onset of nonepileptic seizures peaks in the third decade, and functional motor symptoms have their peak onset in the fourth decade (American Psychiatric Association, 
   2022
). Across different medical specialties and presentations, individuals who are affected by FD are usually younger, peak prevalence in the middle of their 30s (Hausteiner-Wiehle & Hungerer, 
   2020
; Yates & Feldman, 
   2016
). Regarding FD by Proxy, the vast majority of victims are younger than 5
   years
of age (Galvin et al., 
   2005
).

In an epidemiological
            epidemiological
          study conducted by the World Health Organization (Üstun & Sartorius, 
            1995
         ), approximately 5500 patients in primary care practices across 15 different study centers were examined in southern and western European countries, Africa, Asia, the USA, and South America. Syndromes of SSD were increased in South American centers. The Epidemiological Catchment Area Study (Robins & Regier, 
            1991
         ) in the USA revealed increased prevalence rates of syndromes of multiple persistent somatic symptoms in Black women and men. In a study in British primary care practices, individuals with a European background showed significant lower prevalence rates of somatic symptom report compared to individuals with an Asian background (Farooq et al., 
            1995
         ). However, these studies are dated from the 1990s and their results are outdated, thus they should be interpreted carefully. Studies demonstrated no differences between patients with IAD and the general population
            population
         in terms of race or ethnicity (Scarella et al., 
            2019
         ).
